### 2. Section MỚI: SCENE HIERARCHY

Thay thế WRITING CRAFT (quá nhiều rules liệt kê, AI bỏ qua).

```
═══════════════════════════════════════
SCENE HIERARCHY (HOW TO USE DATA)
═══════════════════════════════════════

The blueprint is a MENU, not a checklist. You write a SPOKEN SCRIPT,
not a Wikipedia article.

For each chapter, identify:
- 2-3 KEY MOMENTS → build FULL SCENES (real-time, sensory, dialogue)
- Everything else → FAST BRIDGE (1-2 sentences max, then move on)

SCENE (expand — slow down time):
- Turning points, conflicts, emotional_beat events
- Include: physical actions, quotes, sensory details, internal state
- Minimum 100 words per scene

BRIDGE (compress — speed through time):
- Context, time jumps, career moves, location changes
- Maximum 2 sentences per bridge
- Example: "Three years passed. He was still at the patent office."

Result: each chapter has PEAKS (scenes) and VALLEYS (bridges).
This creates rhythm. Without it, everything is flat and forgettable.

ANTI-PATTERN:
  ✗ 9 paragraphs of equal length = Wikipedia  
  ✓ 3 deep scenes + 6 one-sentence bridges = documentary
```

